Data-Driven Exploration of R User Community Globally

Ben Ubah, Claudia Vitolo and Rick Pack

September 12, 2019

Introduction

R is a programming language and environment for statistical computing and data visualization. An important component of the R ecosystem is its powerful user community that has continued to expand around the world over the years. After announcing an R-Ladies focused open-source dynamic dashboard that we built using R and Javascript, we have now extended that work to encompass all R user groups organized on Meetup. R-Ladies is a world-wide organization to promote gender diversity in the R community. R-Ladies chapters are fully organized on Meetup. Most R user groups around the world are also organized on Meetup. Meetup provides an important API that aids in the retrieval of public information about groups organized on its platform.

In this article, we present our motivation for this work, the challenges we faced and how we surmounted them, the tools and procedures, as well as highlights on our final product.

Why a dashboard to explore R user groups globally now?

  1. Overview: We sought to present an objective representation of Rs popularity that would help members of the data science community accurately judge trends. By making our solution open-source and data-driven, we maximize transparency and enhance trustworthiness. This dashboard also helps leaders understand their user groups in a broader context while revealing opportunities for potential leaders to initiate new groups. Finally, the depiction of global distribution contributes to an important and evolving story about trends and opportunities in different parts of the world.
  Chart showing Cumulative Growth of R User Groups
  1. Communities can flourish more easily when a unified, easily accessible and trusted resource presents information about its members and activity. Information regarding R user groups is spread across several sources and each source, while valuable, displays only a portion of available information. A list of some sources we found are:

  • Meetup.com: https://www.meetup.com/topics/r-project-for-statistical-computing/

  • Jumping Rivers: https://jumpingrivers.github.io/meetingsR/r-user-groups.html

  • R-Ladies: https://gqueiroz.shinyapps.io/rshinylady/

  • RConsortium: https://www.meetup.com/pro/r-user-groups/

We therefore engaged in building a more comprehensive information resource that has aggregated much of the data in the last three sources listed above, which are all organized on the Meetup platform. Incidentally, our next target is to represent groups not organized on Meetup. Jumping Rivers provides a valuable list. Please reach to us if you know of other resources we could explore.

  1. For decision making, R centered organizations may need to geographically measure the presence of R users and groups for events planning, diversity programs, and other activities that could expand the use of the R language in under-represented regions.
  2. New and existing R users would have a resource through which they can find groups near them and then learn how to get involved.
  3. We want to help the thriving R community get even better.

The R Consortium

Two out of three top-level R Consortium projects are focused on R user groups. Appreciative of the R Consortiums support of the R community, the dashboard map is optimized to point Inactive and Unbegun R user groups to R Consortiums RUGS grant program.

Classifying R User Groups

It was quite challenging to classify R user groups on Meetup for reasons including:

  1. The names of some R user groups on Meetup comprise of Location + R User Group (e.g. Las Vegas R User Group), but in their topics or areas of focus on Meetup.com, they do not mention R.

  2. The names of some R user groups on Meetup comprise of Location + Data Science/Analytics Group in their meetup names (e.g.Charleston Data Science), but in their topics or areas of focus, they mention R Project for Statistical Computing.

  3. There are other groups that have Python, Julia, KNIME, Hadoop, etc. in their Meetup names, but yet mention R Project for Statistical Computing in their areas of focus. Some groups combine R and other tools in their names and topics.

  4. Apart from R Project for Statistical Computing, many groups identify with the R language by selecting one of the following topics or areas of focus such as Programming in R, Data Science using R, R Programming Language, and several others.

  5. Other unexpected name stylings were discovered as exemplified by: useRs, PhillyR, BelgradeR, etc.

It was significantly easier to find R-Ladies groups on Meetup because R-Ladies maintains a consistent naming structure across all groups - R-Ladies + Location (e.g.R-Ladies Madison). Only one find_groups() call from the meetupr package was sufficient.

Our Solution

Curtis Kephart generously provided us a key to solving this problem - a technique based on string matching that he uses to retrieve upcoming R events. We extended his approach to:

  • Retrieving all data science groups on Meetup (7700 +) and using string matching to select groups that contain strings like r user, r-user,r-lab,phillyr,rug,bioconductor,r-data,rug in their Meetup URL names. We then performed a second round of string matching to search for strings like programming-in-r, r-programming-, -using-r, r-language, and r-project-for-statistical in the groups topics field.

  • Retrieving all user groups that mention r-project-for-statistical-computing in their topics separately.

  • Retrieving all R-Ladies groups separately. We tried to use string matching to retrieve R-Ladies groups from the data science groups above but some groups were left out.

  • Combining all the resulting data frames and removing duplicates.

We thus classified R user groups as groups that mention R in their names or in their topics. Every other approach we tried left out some R user groups. If you have any further ideas, we would be glad to hear from you.

What Was Achieved

For the R user groups dashboard, the following was achieved:

  1. We used the meetupr package to extract R user groups from Meetup.com
  2. Improved the existing find_groups() and get_events() functions in meetupr to meet our requirements. and switched from Meetup API keys to OAuth 2.0 authentication system
  3. Transformed the data retrieved from Meetup via meetupr from data frames to JSON, GeoJSON and CSV
  4. Stored the data by committing the JSON/GeoJSON/CSV files to the GitHub repository of the project.
  5. Developed a static HTML dashboard interface based on an open-source Bootstrap template
  6. Rendered the stored data via the dashboard interface
  7. Automated the process of extracting R user groups, data transformation and storage.
  8. Deployed it via GitHub Pages

Switching from Meetup API keys to OAuth 2.0 Authentication System

During our work, Meetup announced a removal of keys from their authentication system and a migration to the OAuth 2.0 system which normally operates in an interactive session via a web browser. We implemented this migration for our code which runs in a non-interactive session over Travis by encrypting a locally generated token that is automatically cached by httr.

This token was generated in an interactive session and cached to a file named .httr-oauth in the current working directory, we saved it as an .rds file, encrypted it using openssl and pushed it to our repo. During each Travis build or Cron Job, Travis decrypts the token and it is loaded into the R scripts that make Meetup API calls. The ideas for this approach were borrowed from this vignette on googlesheets and Travis documentation

The sodium package as seen in this article provides valuable encryption/decryption functionality as it could be adopted on all operating systems, on Travis, AppVeyor, and r-hub. We hope to explore this in the future for this project.

Some Highlights from the Dashboard

  1. A leaflet map with markers and pop-ups filled with information about the user groups membership, events, and status (active, inactive, or unbegun).
  1. A cluster map to aggregate markers in clusters and provide cluster counts using leaflet-markercluster.js Javascript library.
  1. Top destinations for R user groups based on membership across 6 regions.

The Tools

To accomplish the following, we used a mix of the tools listed below:

  1. R, RStudio and the following packages:
    • meetupr, curl, jsonlite and leafletR
  2. Javascript and the following libraries: jquery.js, d3.js, echarts.js, leaflet.js, leaflet-markercluster.js and lodash.js
  3. Gentelella Admin Dashboard Bootstrap HTML template
  4. Travis CI to build the project, execute R scripts and bash commands
  5. Bash commands to call R scripts and commit modified files to GitHub

How We Achieved It

R (for data-analysis) and JavaScript (for data-presentation) are the core tools employed to develop our solution considering the variety of options provided by this mix in terms of interactivity, automation and deployment. We applied the following procedure:

  1. We used the meetupr R package to retrieve R User Groups from meetup.com.
  2. We further analyzed this data by computing several summaries. We used the leafletR package to transform our data frame to GeoJSON. We used this GeoJSON file to create a leaflet map using leaflet.js. In this map, R user groups are separated into three groups with markers of three color categories: Active (blue), Inactive (dark-blue), and Unbegun (orange):
  • Active groups have had an event in the past 180 days or have an upcoming event in the future
  • Inactive groups have not had an event in the past 180 days and do not have an upcoming event
  • Unbegun groups have not had an event in the past and none are planned for the future
  1. Persisted all data and our summaries in CSV / JSON files. After each Travis build, the data and our summaries get updated directly from the Meetup API.
  2. We wrote bash commands to run our R scripts, and commit updated CSV / JSON files to GitHub after every Travis build.
  3. We setup Travis Cron Jobs to build this project daily and update our data. This update happens around 09:45AM UTC.
  4. We then customized the Gentelella Admin Dashboard Bootstrap HTML template to our requirements.
  5. Rendered our summaries via widgets on this dashboard. Used Javascript/libraries to produce maps, charts and tables.

The Final Product

The final product is a dashboard for R User Groups that is updated daily via Travis, built using R and JavaScript and hosted via GitHub Pages.

At the time of writing, there are 907 R User Groups composed of 679,913 + members, across 83 countries, 408 cities, with more than 16,600+ past events and 500+ upcoming events. 64% of R user groups are active, 25% are inactive, and 12% are unbegun. Unbegun groups have members but have not started organizing events yet. Our observation is that members are added to the R community daily.

Feedback

We are in hopes of expanding the features of this dashboard beyond its current state and we would love to hear from you if you have any ideas or find issues. We have received significant feedback from R users and these have helped us update our string matching process, helping us discover more user groups that mention R in their names and in their Meetup topics. Through these modifications, we have seen user-group count increase from 600+ to 900+ and several other figures have been automatically updated.

Feel free to Follow / Star the project at its GitHub repo: https://github.com/benubah/r-community-explorer/
